WikiText-2 test, n_ctx 512, non-overlapping windows, oracle pinned to fp32 kv.
q4_k_m is the mixed llama.cpp quant (132 q5_0, 13 q8_0, 12 q4_k, 12 q6_k here).
engine vs llama-perplexity on the same gguf:

  q4_k_m  16 chunks   engine 18.1301   oracle 18.0497   +0.45%
  q4_k_m   4 chunks   engine 13.5675   oracle 13.4804   +0.65%
  q6_k    16 chunks   engine 17.7689   oracle 17.6720   +0.55%
  q6_k     4 chunks   engine 13.3314   oracle 13.2303   +0.76%

all within the 1% weight-quant budget (docs/VERIFICATION.md layer 4).

## Phase 6 (Accelerate prefill)

matmul_accel dequantizes the weight once then issues one cblas_sgemm
(-framework Accelerate, DBINFER_HAVE_ACCELERATE). measured against the scalar
reference matmul (the naive triple loop, not the NEON matvec) on a 512-row
batch, tests/accel_matmul_test. M3 Max, single call, average of 20.

  matmul [m=512 out=512 in=896]   scalar 156.463 ms   accel 0.316 ms   494x

max abs error accel vs scalar 1.5e-5, within the 1e-3 GEMM tolerance. the
wrapper is not wired into forward(): decode still runs one token at a time, so
the default decode path and its perplexity are byte-for-byte unchanged. the
figure sizes the headroom a batched prefill would unlock against the scalar
reference, and is the reason llama-bench's pp512 outruns this engine.

## Phase 7 (KV cache streaming) — 2026-07-19

Ring-buffer KV cache with attention sinks (StreamingLLM), behind --kv-window.
Streaming perplexity feeds one continuous context with monotonically rising
position, per-token NLL bucketed every 512 positions. WikiText-2 test,
qwen2.5-0.5b F16, window 256, first 8 buckets (4096 tokens).

  ./build/release/engine -m qwen2.5-0.5b.gguf --perplexity wiki.test.raw \
    --ppl-stream --kv-window 256 --kv-sink {0,4} --ppl-chunks 8

  pos          naive (sink 0)   sinks (sink 4)
  0-511            95.6956          16.2858
  512-1023         93.9265          19.4518
  1024-1535       105.8915          17.3745
  1536-2047        90.3526          18.2041
  2048-2559        78.8882          14.3412
  2560-3071       117.9712          19.4920
  3072-3583       115.2568          18.2693
  3584-4095       114.7031          21.7222
  stream PPL      100.704792        18.018553

past the 256-token window the naive ring evicts the initial tokens and stays
stuck near 90-118. four pinned sinks hold it flat at 14-22, tracking the dense
full-context range. sinks are the whole difference; without them the ring is
unusable. --ppl-stream requires --kv-window > 0 (the dense cache would run pos
past context_length). default decode, parity, and dense perplexity unchanged.

### int8 KV (--kv-int8), dense, WikiText-2 16 chunks

  ./build/release/engine -m qwen2.5-0.5b.gguf --perplexity wiki.test.raw \
    --ppl-chunks 16 [--kv-int8] [--kv-sink N]

  fp32 KV                                       17.699375
  int8 KV, per-head absmax scale                18.854920   +6.53%
  int8 KV, per-block(32) scale                  18.275141   +3.25%
  int8 KV, per-channel K, no fp32 sink          17.715029   +0.089%
  int8 KV, per-channel K + 4 fp32 sinks         17.710983   +0.066%

per-token quant (per-head or per-block-32) loses 3-6% because one spiking K
channel inflates the scale for its whole slice, crushing the rest. K outliers
are channel-consistent (KIVI), so a scale per head_dim channel, shared across a
32-token group and requantized from a small fp32 residual as the group fills,
cuts the loss to 0.089% on its own. pinning the first 4 tokens (BOS and the
attention sinks, the outlier tokens) in fp32 trims it to 0.066%. values stay
per-block(32) per-token. both configs meet the 0.5% budget; the shipped default
is per-channel K + 4 fp32 sinks (--kv-sink 4). --kv-int8 stays opt-in and the
fp32 dense cache is the default, byte-for-byte unchanged (PPL 17.699375 here
matches the pre-change run and matvec_determinism_test stays bitwise).

## Phase 8 (GBNF grammar-constrained decoding)

Grammar masking tests every vocabulary token against the automaton per decode
step and sets rejected tokens to -inf before the sampler pipeline. Measured on
qwen2.5-0.5b Q8_0, prompt "Write JSON:\n", temp 1.0, seed 5, engine mask
single-threaded. tok/s is the two-length delta 200/(wall(216)-wall(16)) so the
fixed model-load and prefill cancel.

  ./build/release/engine -m qwen2.5-0.5b-q8_0.gguf -p "Write JSON:\n" \
    --temp 1.0 -s 5 -n {16,216} [--grammar grammars/json.gbnf]

  grammar off   90.09 tok/s
  grammar on    12.94 tok/s   +66.2 ms/token   6.96x

overhead is the per-step scan of the 151936-token vocabulary. most tokens are
rejected at their first codepoint. the batch harness (tools/grammar_json_gen)
splits that scan across the 12 P-cores, holding ~1.5 s/generation including the
model forward.

### JSON gate: 1000 completions

  ./build/release/tools/grammar_json_gen -m qwen2.5-0.5b-q8_0.gguf \
    -g grammars/json.gbnf -c 1000 -n 64 --temp 1.0 -p "Return one JSON object:\n"
  tools/.venv/bin/python -c "json.loads each line"

  1000/1000 parse as valid JSON  (671 completed naturally, 329 closed along the
  shortest grammar-valid suffix when the 64-token sampling budget ran out).

## Phase 9 (speculative decoding)

A quantized draft (qwen2.5-0.5b Q4_0) proposes k tokens greedily; the F16
target (qwen2.5-0.5b) verifies them in one forward_chunk over k+1 positions,
accepting the longest prefix where the draft token equals the target's greedy
argmax and taking the target's argmax on the first mismatch. Greedy, so the
output is token-identical to target-only decode by construction.

Token-identical gate (--print-ids, greedy, diff vs spec off), n 64:

  ./build/release/engine -m qwen2.5-0.5b.gguf -p "<prompt>" -n 64 --print-ids \
    [--draft-model qwen2.5-0.5b-q4_0.gguf --draft-k {4,8}]

  prompt "The quick brown fox"              k=4 IDENTICAL  rate 0.7656
  prompt "The quick brown fox"              k=8 IDENTICAL  rate 0.6591
  prompt "Once upon a time in a distant land" k=4 IDENTICAL  rate 0.6000
  prompt "Once upon a time in a distant land" k=8 IDENTICAL  rate 0.3487

Wall clock, prompt "Once upon a time in a distant land", 12 P-cores, decode
delta 128/(wall(144)-wall(16)) so model load and prefill cancel, median of 3:

  spec off        8.54 tok/s
  spec on k=4     9.62 tok/s   1.13x

  (prior fused-free number was spec on k=4 4.80 tok/s, 0.55x.)

matmul_quant now runs a fused batched f16 kernel on the verify path: each
weight element is dequantized once and accumulated into all k+1 token rows, so
the target weights are read from the mmap once per round instead of k+1 times.
The reduction over `in` stays sequential and uses explicit std::fma, matched by
the same std::fma in the per-row matvec_f16, so every verify logit is
bit-identical to per-token decode (chunked_prefill_test, matvec_determinism_test)
and the greedy stream stays token-identical to spec-off (--print-ids diff,
k=4 and k=8, both prompts IDENTICAL). Speedup is now above 1x because the
verify projections are no longer weight-bandwidth-bound on the k+1 rows.

## Phase 10: custom model format (dbmf)

Container format for the same weights and hyperparams a gguf carries, laid out
for this engine. Numbers from qwen2.5-0.5b, converted with tools/gguf_to_dbmf.

File size (F16 model, 290 tensors):

  gguf                         994156352 B   100.00%
  dbmf raw                     995872256 B   100.17%   (+1.72 MB)
  dbmf compressed (f16 huff)   847547904 B    85.25%   (-146.6 MB)

dbmf-raw is slightly LARGER than gguf: every tensor data offset is padded to a
16384-byte page (Apple Silicon page size) so a later Metal backend can wrap the
mmap zero-copy via newBufferWithBytesNoCopy. The padding overhead here is
+0.17% (1.72 MB over 290 tensors), the documented cost of the alignment.

Compression is DFloat11/ZipNN-inspired: each f16 splits into a low-entropy high
byte (sign, exponent, top mantissa bits) canonical-huffman coded, and a raw low
byte. Achieved 14.75% reduction on this model. That is materially below the
~20% some papers report; f16 low-byte mantissa noise is near-incompressible and
is stored raw, so the ceiling is the high-byte plane alone. Reported as-is.

Load-to-first-logit (warm page cache, engine -n 1, median of 3):

  gguf                 0.57 s
  dbmf raw             0.57 s   mmap-direct, identical to gguf
  dbmf compressed      5.18 s   decodes every f16 tensor once at load

Compressed mode trades ~4.6 s of one-time decode for a 15% smaller file, a
storage/distribution mode. Raw mode stays the mmap-direct default.

Dedup: identical (dtype, size, xxhash64) tensors with byte-equal contents are
stored once, both table entries share the offset. qwen2.5 ties its embeddings
and the gguf already omits the lm_head, so this model has no duplicate tensor
and dedup saves 0 B here. The mechanism is proven on a synthetic twin in
dbmf_convert_test (tied tensor shares one data offset).

Integrity: per-tensor xxhash64 in the table plus an xxhash64 of the header.
DBMF_VERIFY=1 (or read verify=true) rechecks every tensor at load; compressed
tensors are always verified against the stored hash after decode. A flipped
tensor byte is reported by name (dbmf_convert_test corruption gate).

Verdict vs gguf on each claimed axis:
  - indexed access: better. fixed 128-byte table records, O(1) vs gguf's
    sequential variable-length tensor_info parse.
  - integrity: better. gguf carries no per-tensor checksum.
  - Metal zero-copy readiness: better. page-aligned tensor data.
  - load speed (raw): tie. both mmap-direct, same wall time.
  - file size (raw): slightly worse (+0.17%), the alignment trade.
  - file size (compressed): better (-14.75%) at a load-time decode cost.
  - dedup: neutral on this model (nothing to dedup), mechanism present.

## Phase 11 slice (a) (Metal mul_mat_f16 offload)

Backend seam: DBINFER_BACKEND=metal routes tensor::matmul_quant's F16 batched
path (chunked prefill, speculative verify) to a Metal compute kernel. Per-token
decode (matvec_quant) stays CPU. Default is CPU and stays bitwise unchanged.

Machine: Apple M3 Max, 12 P-cores, 48 GB unified memory.
Model: qwen2.5-0.5b.gguf (F16 weights).

Prefill tok/s, 480-token prompt, --prefill-chunk 8. Wall clock isolates prefill
by subtracting a 1-token run (model load + tokenize + one token), 479 prefill
tokens:

                    t(480-tok)   t(1-tok)   prefill s   prefill tok/s
  CPU  (default)      29.11       0.57       28.54        16.8
  Metal offload       17.53       0.69       16.84        28.4

Metal is ~1.7x faster on F16 prefill at this size. The weight buffer is copied
in per matmul here: the gguf mmap aligns tensor data to 32 bytes, below the
16384-byte page newBufferWithBytesNoCopy needs. DBMF tensors are 16 KiB-aligned
and wrap zero-copy (metal_matmul_test proves the wrap succeeds for an aligned
pointer and falls back for an unaligned one); loading the model as DBMF removes
the per-call weight copy.

Per-kernel parity (metal_matmul_test): max_err 0.000e+00 across m in {1,4,7} and
out/in in {32,896,4864}. The shader accumulates in fp32 with the same sequential
fma order as matvec_f16, so it is bitwise identical to the CPU F16 path, well
inside the atol 1e-4 gate. End-to-end greedy output is token-identical to CPU
for 2 prompts (--prefill-chunk 8, --print-ids), no near-tie flips.

## Phase 11 slice (b) (Metal rmsnorm, rope, attention, layer offload)

Backend grows rmsnorm, rope, attention, and a fused per-layer decode. --gpu-layers
N (or DBINFER_GPU_LAYERS) runs the first N blocks of the per-token forward() on
Metal: rmsnorm, QKV/attn/ffn matmuls (mul_mat_f16, m=1), bias, rope, attention,
and the elementwise glue, one command buffer per layer. F16 model on the dense
fp32 cache only. N=0 is pure CPU and stays bitwise unchanged.

Machine: Apple M3 Max, 12 P-cores, 48 GB unified memory.
Model: qwen2.5-0.5b.gguf (F16 weights), 24 blocks.

Per-kernel parity (metal_ops_test) vs the scalar CPU op, atol 1e-4:

  op          shapes                                    max_err
  rmsnorm     rows {1,4} x dim {32,896,4864}            2.384e-07
  rope        nh {2,8,14} seq {1,4} hd {64,128}         4.427e-05
  attention   nh/nkv {14/2,8/8} hd {64,128} pos 1..300  1.192e-07

rmsnorm and attention sum sequentially per output, so they match the CPU
reduction bitwise apart from softmax exp (attention max 1.2e-7, rmsnorm 2.4e-7 from
the scalar auto-vectorized sum). rope diverges only because fp32 pow/cos/sin
replace the double CPU transcendentals; the angle error scales with position and
reaches ~1e-4 near pos 2048 for theta 1e6, far past any parity-prompt range.

End-to-end greedy parity, --print-ids, 48 tokens, 2 prompts:

  gpu-layers 24 vs 0 : token-identical (both prompts)
  gpu-layers 12 vs 0 : token-identical (both prompts, mixed CPU/GPU)

No near-tie flips; the fp32 activations and sequential reductions keep the
offloaded stack inside the CPU logits.

Decode tok/s, short prompt, 128 tokens, wall clock minus a 1-token run:

  gpu-layers   decode tok/s
  0 (CPU)         8.50
  12              7.27
  24              6.96

The GPU per-token path loses to the threaded i8mm CPU path, as expected: m=1
GEMV is memory-bound and tiny, and each offloaded layer pays a command-buffer
submit plus a KV-history copy into a fresh device buffer. Per-layer batching
avoids the per-op-sync collapse (24 syncs/token, not ~250). Beating CPU decode
needs quant matvec on Metal (future) or fusing all offloaded layers into one
command buffer per token; prefill (slice a) already wins at 1.7x. Numbers are
reported as measured, not tuned.

## Phase 11 M1 (Metal quantized decode) — 2026-07-19

Adds Q8_0/Q4_0 matvec on the GPU, a page-aligned dense fp32 KV cache the backend
wraps no-copy (shared, zero per-token copy), and one command buffer per token
for all offloaded layers. --gpu-layers now runs Q8_0/Q4_0 models (F16 still
works). Weights copy to the device once at setup, not per token.

Machine: Apple M3 Max, 12 P-cores, 48 GB unified memory.
Models: qwen2.5-0.5b Q8_0/Q4_0/F16, 24 blocks.

Bitwise gate (tests/metal_quant_test), GPU vs CPU scalar, memcmp-identical:

  activation quant  rows {1,4} x in {896,4864}                bit-exact
  Q8_0 matvec       out/in {896,4864,151936-lm_head}/{896,4864} bit-exact
  Q4_0 matvec       same shapes                                bit-exact

the integer block dot is order-free; the fp32 block accumulation contracts to
one fma per block matching the scalar reference under clang -ffp-contract=on.
half(d) through the hardware round-to-nearest-even matches f32_to_f16 for the
activation scales. no rounding divergence.

End-to-end greedy, --print-ids, 48 tokens, 2 prompts, gpu-layers 24 vs 0:

  F16   both prompts               token-identical
  Q8_0  'The quick brown fox'      diverges at token 30 (near-tie flip)
  Q8_0  'Once upon a time ...'     diverges at token 37 (near-tie flip)
  Q4_0  'The quick brown fox'      token-identical
  Q4_0  'Once upon a time ...'     diverges at token 5 (near-tie flip)

F16 stays token-identical: its kernels are bitwise (mul_mat_f16, rmsnorm,
attention) apart from rope's fp32 transcendentals. Quant divergences are the
documented near-tie behavior, not a matvec error. GPU quant matvec is bitwise
to the scalar reference (gate above); the default CPU decode runs the i8mm
kernel, whose reduction order differs within 1e-6. Comparing GPU against a
scalar-kernel CPU decode (DBINFER_QUANT_KERNEL=scalar) moves the first flip late
(Q8_0 token 30/37, Q4_0 fox 48/48 identical); the residual comes from the GPU
rope fp32 pow/cos/sin gap flipping near-tie argmax tokens.

Perplexity, WikiText-2 test, Q8_0, 4 chunks (non-overlapping 256-tok windows):

  gpu-layers 0    PPL 13.382441
  gpu-layers 24   PPL 13.389829   +0.055%

within noise, far inside the 1% weight-quant budget.

Decode tok/s, Q8_0, 128 tokens, wall(n=129)-wall(n=1), median of 3:

  gpu-layers 0 (CPU threaded i8mm)   84.3
  gpu-layers 24 (GPU)                26.4
  (old F16 GPU per-layer path, slice b, for context: 6.96)

honest read: GPU decode is 3.8x the old F16 GPU path (6.96 -> 26.4) and clears
the 8.5 F16 CPU number, but sits 3.2x below the CPU threaded i8mm reference
(84.3). weights no longer copy per token, so the loss is not weight bandwidth:
at ~500 MB/token and ~400 GB/s the read floor is ~1.3 ms, against ~38 ms/token
measured. the cost is GPU underutilization at m=1. the per-row matvec runs one
thread per output row, attention one thread per head (14 threads), rmsnorm one
thread per row (a single thread), so most of the GPU sits idle every dispatch.
one command buffer per token already removed the per-layer submit collapse (1
wait/token, not 24).

M2 (fusion) should target occupancy first: a simdgroup-per-output-row reduction
for the quant matvec (fill the 32 lanes per row instead of one thread), a
parallel rmsnorm/softmax reduction, and attention parallelized across positions,
not just heads. that is where the 38 ms/token goes.

